{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff: taxonomy labels can be correct in local builder logic yet omitted/mutated when wiring into the API request object. Test should run classifier module + real request-construction path + stub transport that captures outbound payload. Rejected System because behavior text is about request content, not real network/OS effects (`request sent ... includes ... labels`). Rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model judgment, only payload fields.","test_description":"Invoke classification with a known taxonomy using a fake API endpoint/client that records the outgoing request. Assert every configured label appears in the transmitted payload and no label is dropped across wiring layers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is normalization/validation logic on returned label value; this is a single-function decision boundary and does not require real module interaction to surface. Rejected Integration because behavior text constrains only value mapping (`returns a label that is not in the taxonomy` -> `returns \"unknown\"`), not cross-module state propagation.","test_description":"Call the normalization/response-mapping function with an out-of-taxonomy label fixture and assert the final result is exactly `unknown`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.74,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure determinism of normalization for identical input; one local function/object boundary is sufficient. Rejected higher levels because behavior explicitly scopes to `identical raw API responses` and `normalization step`, disqualifying need for real infra or model variability.","test_description":"Run normalization repeatedly on the same raw response fixture and assert output label is identical across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live AI outputs (`repeated live API calls`) and label consistency under model/provider nondeterminism. Mocked responses would hide real drift/variance. Rejected Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification calls, not a multi-agent/multi-step decision pipeline.","test_description":"Execute multiple real classification calls against the provider for identical document+taxonomy; record raw responses and final labels. Assert label stability when raw provider outputs are equivalent, and allow label changes only when provider output content changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.77,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is between budgeting logic and dispatch control: module may compute budget correctly but still dispatch an over-budget request (or fail to apply truncate/reject policy) when components are wired. Integration with stub transport catches this real handoff failure. Rejected System because enforcement is `before dispatch`, so real network/OS is not required.","test_description":"Configure a small budget and run classification with over-budget input using the real request-builder + dispatch orchestrator and a stub API client. Assert policy behavior (truncate or reject) occurs before send, and verify whether send is blocked or payload is reduced per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI provider call and provider-side token accounting; stubs can always return compliant usage and hide real budget overruns. Because behavior passes through a real AI API and correctness depends on model/provider-produced usage metadata, Agentic is the safer minimum than Integration. Rejected Workflow because only one agentic step is required.","test_description":"Send representative documents to the real provider with configured budget and capture provider-reported usage metrics from responses. Assert reported total tokens are within configured limit for the typical-doc fixture set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.32,"Agentic":0.66,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across local modules (error classifier, backoff/wait policy, retry loop, caller response). A deterministic stub that returns rate-limit then success can reproduce the real failure. Rejected System because behavior does not require real network timing primitives; it requires correct control flow on a known signal (`API signals ... rate is too high`). Rejected Agentic because no model-output-quality dependence.","test_description":"Use a stub provider that returns rate-limit error first, then success. Assert module performs wait/backoff and retries, eventually returning success to caller instead of surfacing the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.17,"Integration":0.79,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
